# Phase 6: Domain Event Dual-Path

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:phoenix_pubsub, "~> 2.1"},
  {:jason, "~> 1.4"}
])
```

## What Changed

Phase 2 wired dual-path delivery for Worker and EffectDispatcher — the
two publish sites that live inside `rho` core and `rho_web`. Phase 6
extends the same pattern to **domain-level publishers** in `rho_stdlib`
and `rho_frameworks`.

Every `Comms.publish` in those apps now has a matching
`maybe_broadcast_event` or `maybe_broadcast_emit` call that sends the
same data through the LiveEvents PubSub path.

```
MultiAgent.do_delegate ──┬──► Comms.publish("rho.task.requested")
                         └──► broadcaster.broadcast_event(:task_requested, ...)

AgentJobs.publish_event ──┬──► Comms.publish("rho.session.<sid>.events.<type>")
                          └──► broadcaster.broadcast_emit(payload, ...)

Lenses.score_via_llm ──┬──► Comms.publish("rho.session.<sid>.events.lens_score_update")
                       └──► broadcaster.broadcast_event(:lens_score_update, ...)
```

## The boundary constraint

`rho_stdlib` and `rho_frameworks` cannot depend on `rho_web`. They
use the same dependency-inversion pattern as Worker: read the configured
broadcaster module from Application env and call it conditionally.

```elixir
defp maybe_broadcast_event(kind, session_id, agent_id, data)
     when is_binary(session_id) do
  case Application.get_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster) do
    nil -> :ok
    mod -> mod.broadcast_event(kind, session_id, agent_id, data)
  end
end

defp maybe_broadcast_event(_, _, _, _), do: :ok
```

Unlike Worker (which caches the module in GenServer state), these are
stateless tool/context functions — they read the env on each call. This
is fine for event-publishing hot paths that already do a `Comms.publish`
(which itself does ETS lookups).

## Publish sites covered

### rho_stdlib — MultiAgent

| Function | Event kind | Broadcaster call |
|---|---|---|
| `route_by_capability/4` | `:task_requested` | `broadcast_event` |
| `do_delegate/2` | `:task_requested` | `broadcast_event` |
| `execute_delegate_lite/4` | `:task_requested` | `broadcast_event` |
| `publish_lite_event/3` | emit types (`:text_delta`, `:tool_start`, etc.) | `broadcast_emit` |
| `publish_lite_completion/3` | `:task_completed` | `broadcast_event` |
| `execute_spawn/8` | `:agent_spawned` | `broadcast_event` |
| `execute_send_message/3` | `:message_sent` | `broadcast_event` |
| `execute_broadcast_message/3` | `:broadcast` | `broadcast_event` |

### rho_frameworks — AgentJobs

| Function | Event kind | Broadcaster call |
|---|---|---|
| `publish_completion/3` | `:task_completed` | `broadcast_event` |
| `publish_event/3` | emit types | `broadcast_emit` |

### rho_frameworks — Domain modules

| Module | Function | Event kind |
|---|---|---|
| `SkeletonGenerator` | `publish_started/2` | `:task_requested` |
| `Proficiency` | `publish_delegation/4` | `:task_requested` |
| `LensTools` | `lens_dashboard` tool | `:lens_dashboard_init` |
| `Lenses` | `maybe_publish_score_update/3` | `:lens_score_update` |

## Intentionally Comms-only

These `Comms.publish` calls do **not** get a LiveEvents broadcast:

| Module | Topic | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `DataTable.Server` | `rho.session.<sid>.events.data_table` | Internal invalidation; LiveView subscribes directly via Comms for snapshot refetches. Will migrate in a later phase. |
| `LiveRender` | `ui_spec_delta`, `ui_spec` | Custom streaming protocol with incremental element accumulation. Needs its own migration path. |
| `Hiring.Simulation` | `rho.hiring.*` | Demo module, not production. |
| `Hiring.Tools` | `rho.hiring.scores.submitted` | Demo module, not production. |

## Demonstration

### Setup

```elixir
{:ok, _} = Phoenix.PubSub.PG2.start_link(name: Rho.PubSub)

defmodule RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event do
  @enforce_keys [:kind, :session_id]
  defstruct [:kind, :session_id, :agent_id, :timestamp, data: %{}]
end

defmodule RhoWeb.LiveEvents do
  alias RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event
  @pubsub Rho.PubSub

  def subscribe(sid), do: Phoenix.PubSub.subscribe(@pubsub, topic(sid))
  def broadcast(sid, %Event{} = e), do: Phoenix.PubSub.broadcast(@pubsub, topic(sid), e)

  def event(kind, sid, aid \\ nil, data \\ %{}) do
    %Event{
      kind: kind,
      session_id: sid,
      agent_id: aid,
      timestamp: System.monotonic_time(:millisecond),
      data: data
    }
  end

  def topic(sid), do: "rho_lv:session:#{sid}"
end

# Simulate the broadcaster module that rho_stdlib/rho_frameworks call
defmodule FakeBroadcaster do
  def broadcast_event(kind, session_id, agent_id, data) do
    event = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.event(kind, session_id, agent_id, data)
    RhoWeb.LiveEvents.broadcast(session_id, event)
    :ok
  end

  def broadcast_emit(%{type: _} = emit_event, session_id, agent_id) do
    data =
      emit_event
      |> Map.delete(:type)
      |> Map.put(:session_id, session_id)
      |> Map.put(:agent_id, agent_id)

    event = %RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{
      kind: emit_event.type,
      session_id: session_id,
      agent_id: agent_id,
      timestamp: System.monotonic_time(:millisecond),
      data: data
    }

    RhoWeb.LiveEvents.broadcast(session_id, event)
    :ok
  end
end

# Wire up the broadcaster (matches config :rho, :event_broadcaster)
Application.put_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster, FakeBroadcaster)
```

### Simulate MultiAgent task delegation

This mimics `do_delegate/2` publishing a `:task_requested` event through
both paths. A subscriber should receive the LiveEvents event with the
same data that Comms would carry.

```elixir
session_id = "phase6-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
agent_id = "#{session_id}/worker-1"

RhoWeb.LiveEvents.subscribe(session_id)

# Simulate the maybe_broadcast_event call from MultiAgent.do_delegate
task_data = %{
  task_id: "task_42",
  session_id: session_id,
  agent_id: agent_id,
  parent_agent_id: "#{session_id}/primary",
  role: "analyst",
  task: "Analyze the data",
  max_steps: 30
}

# This is what MultiAgent does after Comms.publish:
case Application.get_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster) do
  nil -> :ok
  mod -> mod.broadcast_event(:task_requested, session_id, agent_id, task_data)
end

# Verify receipt
received =
  receive do
    %RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{} = e -> e
  after
    500 -> nil
  end

if received do
  IO.puts("✓ Received :#{received.kind} event")
  IO.puts("  session_id: #{received.session_id}")
  IO.puts("  agent_id: #{received.agent_id}")
  IO.puts("  task_id: #{received.data.task_id}")
  IO.puts("  role: #{received.data.role}")
else
  IO.puts("✗ No event received")
end
```

### Simulate lite worker event streaming

This mimics `publish_lite_event/3` and `publish_lite_completion/3` — the
lite worker emit path that goes through `broadcast_emit` for streaming
events and `broadcast_event` for the final completion.

```elixir
session_id = "phase6-lite-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
agent_id = "#{session_id}/lite-1"

RhoWeb.LiveEvents.subscribe(session_id)

# Simulate streaming events (broadcast_emit path)
emit_events = [
  %{type: :step_start, step: 1, max_steps: 5, agent_id: agent_id, session_id: session_id, lite: true},
  %{type: :text_delta, text: "Working...", agent_id: agent_id, session_id: session_id, lite: true},
  %{type: :tool_start, name: "bash", args: %{}, call_id: "c1", agent_id: agent_id, session_id: session_id, lite: true},
  %{type: :tool_result, name: "bash", output: "ok", status: :ok, call_id: "c1", agent_id: agent_id, session_id: session_id, lite: true}
]

for emit <- emit_events do
  broadcaster = Application.get_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster)
  broadcaster.broadcast_emit(emit, session_id, agent_id)
end

# Simulate completion (broadcast_event path)
completion_data = %{session_id: session_id, agent_id: agent_id, status: :ok, result: "Done."}
broadcaster = Application.get_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster)
broadcaster.broadcast_event(:task_completed, session_id, agent_id, completion_data)

# Drain all events
received =
  Enum.reduce_while(1..10, [], fn _, acc ->
    receive do
      %RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{} = e -> {:cont, [e | acc]}
    after
      100 -> {:halt, acc}
    end
  end)
  |> Enum.reverse()

kinds = Enum.map(received, & &1.kind)
IO.puts("Received #{length(received)} events:")
for e <- received, do: IO.puts("  #{e.kind}")

expected = [:step_start, :text_delta, :tool_start, :tool_result, :task_completed]

if kinds == expected do
  IO.puts("\n✓ Lite worker event sequence correct — streaming + completion both delivered")
else
  IO.puts("\n✗ Mismatch")
  IO.inspect(kinds, label: "got")
end
```

### Simulate lens score update

Lens events (`lens_score_update`, `lens_dashboard_init`) previously only
traveled via Comms. Now they also broadcast through LiveEvents, which
means the `LensDashboardProjection` can eventually consume them from
either path.

```elixir
session_id = "phase6-lens-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
agent_id = "#{session_id}/primary"

RhoWeb.LiveEvents.subscribe(session_id)

# Simulate Lenses.maybe_publish_score_update
score_data = %{
  lens_id: 1,
  score: %{
    score_id: 42,
    classification: "augmented",
    axes: [%{name: "Impact", composite: 3.5}, %{name: "Readiness", composite: 4.0}]
  }
}

broadcaster = Application.get_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster)
broadcaster.broadcast_event(:lens_score_update, session_id, agent_id, score_data)

received =
  receive do
    %RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{} = e -> e
  after
    500 -> nil
  end

if received && received.kind == :lens_score_update do
  IO.puts("✓ Received :lens_score_update via LiveEvents")
  IO.puts("  lens_id: #{received.data.lens_id}")
  IO.puts("  classification: #{received.data.score.classification}")
else
  IO.puts("✗ No lens event received")
end
```

### Nil broadcaster safety

When `event_broadcaster` is not configured (CLI mode, tests without
web), the helper is a no-op.

```elixir
Application.put_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster, nil)

# This should silently succeed — no crash, no event
result =
  case Application.get_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster) do
    nil -> :ok
    mod -> mod.broadcast_event(:task_requested, "s1", "a1", %{})
  end

IO.puts("✓ Nil broadcaster returns #{inspect(result)} — safe no-op")

# Restore for any subsequent cells
Application.put_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster, FakeBroadcaster)
```
